1. One trigger per object

Why: Salesforce gives no guarantee about execution order when multiple triggers exist on the same object. Two triggers on Account, both before update — the order is undefined and can change between deployments. If one depends on a field the other sets, you get a bug that reproduces intermittently and never in a sandbox.

Secondary reasons: you can't reason about recursion across files you can't see, and installed managed packages may add their own triggers you don't control (that's the one case where you genuinely have more than one, and you just have to live with it).

Enforcing it. Naming convention <Object>Trigger plus code review is the usual answer. If you want it mechanical, a simple test:

apex
@IsTest
static void enforceOneTriggerPerObject() {
    Map<String, Integer> counts = new Map<String, Integer>();

    for (ApexTrigger t : [SELECT Name, TableEnumOrId FROM ApexTrigger
                          WHERE NamespacePrefix = null AND Status = 'Active']) {
        Integer c = counts.containsKey(t.TableEnumOrId) ? counts.get(t.TableEnumOrId) : 0;
        counts.put(t.TableEnumOrId, c + 1);
    }

    for (String obj : counts.keySet()) {
        Assert.isTrue(counts.get(obj) <= 1, 'Multiple triggers on ' + obj);
    }
}

NamespacePrefix = null excludes managed packages. This runs in your CI and fails the build the moment someone adds a second one.

