2. Trigger handler framework
Base class

public virtual class TriggerHandler {

    // ---- bypass registry (static: lives for the transaction) ----
    private static Set<String> bypassed = new Set<String>();

    public static void bypass(String handlerName)   { bypassed.add(handlerName); }
    public static void clearBypass(String handlerName) { bypassed.remove(handlerName); }
    public static void clearAllBypasses()           { bypassed.clear(); }
    public static Boolean isBypassed(String handlerName) { return bypassed.contains(handlerName); }

    // ---- test support ----
    @TestVisible private Boolean isTriggerExecuting;
    @TestVisible private TriggerOperation context;

    public TriggerHandler() {
        this.isTriggerExecuting = Trigger.isExecuting;
        this.context = Trigger.operationType;
    }

    public void run() {

        if (!isTriggerExecuting) {
            throw new TriggerHandlerException('run() called outside a trigger context');
        }

        String handlerName = String.valueOf(this).substringBefore(':');
        if (isBypassed(handlerName)) return;

        switch on this.context {
            when BEFORE_INSERT { this.beforeInsert(); }
            when BEFORE_UPDATE { this.beforeUpdate(); }
            when BEFORE_DELETE { this.beforeDelete(); }
            when AFTER_INSERT  { this.afterInsert();  }
            when AFTER_UPDATE  { this.afterUpdate();  }
            when AFTER_DELETE  { this.afterDelete();  }
            when AFTER_UNDELETE { this.afterUndelete(); }
        }
    }

    // ---- overridable no-ops ----
    protected virtual void beforeInsert()  {}
    protected virtual void beforeUpdate()  {}
    protected virtual void beforeDelete()  {}
    protected virtual void afterInsert()   {}
    protected virtual void afterUpdate()   {}
    protected virtual void afterDelete()   {}
    protected virtual void afterUndelete() {}

    public class TriggerHandlerException extends Exception {}
}

String.valueOf(this).substringBefore(':') yields the concrete subclass name — a small trick that lets the base class identify its own subclass without you passing a string in.

The trigger file
apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (
    before insert, before update, before delete,
    after insert, after update, after delete, after undelete
) {
    new AccountTriggerHandler().run();
}

Two lines, always. All seven events registered even if unused — adding an event later means editing the trigger, which means a deployment; registering upfront means you only touch Apex classes.

The concrete handler
apex
public with sharing class AccountTriggerHandler extends TriggerHandler {

    private List<Account> newList;
    private List<Account> oldList;
    private Map<Id, Account> newMap;
    private Map<Id, Account> oldMap;

    public AccountTriggerHandler() {
        this.newList = (List<Account>) Trigger.new;
        this.oldList = (List<Account>) Trigger.old;
        this.newMap  = (Map<Id, Account>) Trigger.newMap;
        this.oldMap  = (Map<Id, Account>) Trigger.oldMap;
    }

    protected override void beforeInsert() {
        AccountService.applyDefaults(newList);
    }

    protected override void beforeUpdate() {
        AccountService.applyDefaults(newList);
        AccountService.validateOwnershipChange(newList, oldMap);
    }

    protected override void afterUpdate() {
        AccountService.syncContactsOnRename(newList, oldMap);
    }
}

Note the layering: trigger → handler → service. The handler is a dispatcher that knows about trigger context; the service holds business logic and takes plain collections. That separation is what makes the logic unit-testable without DML — you can call AccountService.applyDefaults(someList) directly in a test with in-memory records and no database round trip.

What the bypass buys you
apex
// data migration script — skip the sync logic
TriggerHandler.bypass('AccountTriggerHandler');
update tenThousandAccounts;
TriggerHandler.clearAllBypasses();

Also useful in tests when you want to set up data without triggering downstream automation, and in a Contact handler that's updating Accounts and doesn't want the Account handler firing back.

For production-configurable bypass, back it with a hierarchy custom setting so admins can disable a handler for a specific user or profile without a deployment:

apex
private static Boolean isDisabledInSettings(String handlerName) {
    TriggerSettings__c s = TriggerSettings__c.getInstance();
    return s != null && s.Disable_All__c;
}

