3. Bulkification

The rule everyone quotes is "no SOQL/DML in loops." The rule that actually matters is the shape: collect → query once → build a map → iterate.

The four killers

// ❌ 1. SOQL in loop — dies at 101 records
for (Opportunity o : Trigger.new) {
    Account a = [SELECT Id, Rating FROM Account WHERE Id = :o.AccountId];
}

// ❌ 2. DML in loop — dies at 151
for (Opportunity o : Trigger.new) {
    insert new Task(WhatId = o.Id);
}

// ❌ 3. Nested loops — CPU limit at ~200×200
for (Opportunity o : Trigger.new) {
    for (Account a : allAccounts) { if (a.Id == o.AccountId) { ... } }
}

// ❌ 4. Unfiltered query — heap limit / 50k row limit
List<Contact> all = [SELECT Id FROM Contact];

The correct shape

public with sharing class OpportunityService {

    public static void stampAccountTier(List<Opportunity> opps) {

        // ---- PHASE 1: collect keys, no queries ----
        Set<Id> accountIds = new Set<Id>();
        for (Opportunity o : opps) {
            if (o.AccountId != null) accountIds.add(o.AccountId);
        }
        if (accountIds.isEmpty()) return;          // early exit before spending SOQL

        // ---- PHASE 2: one query, selective, only needed fields ----
        Map<Id, Account> accounts = new Map<Id, Account>([
            SELECT Id, AnnualRevenue, Rating
            FROM Account
            WHERE Id IN :accountIds
        ]);

        // ---- PHASE 3: iterate, O(1) lookups only ----
        for (Opportunity o : opps) {
            Account a = accounts.get(o.AccountId);
            if (a == null) continue;
            o.Tier__c = (a.AnnualRevenue > 10000000) ? 'Enterprise' : 'Mid-Market';
        }
    }
}

Same instinct as collapsing an N+1 into a single WHERE id IN (...) — except here the ceiling is hard and the exception is uncatchable.

Patterns worth internalizing

Parent → children in one query (relationship subquery beats two round trips):

apex
for (Account a : [SELECT Id, (SELECT Id, Email FROM Contacts) FROM Account WHERE Id IN :ids]) {
    for (Contact c : a.Contacts) { ... }
}

Aggregate instead of counting in Apex:

apex
for (AggregateResult ar : [SELECT AccountId aid, SUM(Amount) total
                           FROM Opportunity WHERE AccountId IN :ids GROUP BY AccountId]) {
    totals.put((Id) ar.get('aid'), (Decimal) ar.get('total'));
}

Only DML records that actually changed — this is bulkification and recursion defense in one move:

apex
List<Account> toUpdate = new List<Account>();
for (Account a : parents) {
    Decimal computed = totals.containsKey(a.Id) ? totals.get(a.Id) : 0;
    if (a.Total_Opp_Value__c != computed) {     // ← the check
        a.Total_Opp_Value__c = computed;
        toUpdate.add(a);
    }
}
if (!toUpdate.isEmpty()) update toUpdate;

A no-op update still runs the full order of execution on every record. Filtering here can turn 200 pointless saves into zero.

Use Map<Id, sObject> constructor — new Map<Id, Account>([SELECT ...]) keys by Id automatically, no manual loop.

Query fields you need and no more. Every field on 200 records counts against the 6 MB heap

