4. Recursion prevention with static variables

Statics live for the duration of the execution context — the entire transaction, including all nested trigger invocations. That's exactly the scope you want for a guard, and exactly why the naive version fails.

Why the plain boolean is broken
apex
public class Guard { public static Boolean hasRun = false; }

DML on more than 200 records fires the trigger in chunks of 200 as separate, legitimate invocations. Update 450 accounts: chunk 1 sets hasRun = true, chunks 2 and 3 silently skip. You process 200 records and drop 250. Every test under 201 records passes.

The record-scoped version
apex
public class RecursionGuard {

    private static Map<String, Set<Id>> processed = new Map<String, Set<Id>>();

    /**
     * Returns only the Ids not yet processed under this key, and marks them processed.
     * Key convention: 'ClassName.methodName'
     */
    public static Set<Id> claim(String key, Set<Id> candidates) {
        if (!processed.containsKey(key)) processed.put(key, new Set<Id>());
        Set<Id> seen = processed.get(key);

        Set<Id> fresh = new Set<Id>(candidates);
        fresh.removeAll(seen);
        seen.addAll(fresh);
        return fresh;
    }

    public static Boolean hasProcessed(String key, Id recordId) {
        return processed.containsKey(key) && processed.get(key).contains(recordId);
    }

    @TestVisible
    public static void reset() { processed.clear(); }
}

Usage:

apex
public static void syncContactsOnRename(List<Account> accts, Map<Id, Account> oldMap) {

    Set<Id> toProcess = RecursionGuard.claim('AccountService.syncContacts', oldMap.keySet());
    if (toProcess.isEmpty()) return;

    for (Account a : accts) {
        if (!toProcess.contains(a.Id)) continue;
        // ...
    }
}

Record-scoped, so chunk 2 of a 450-record update proceeds normally while genuine re-entry on the same record is blocked. The per-key map means two independent pieces of logic on the same object don't block each other.

Statics: what to actually know
Behavior                                                                            	Consequence
Scope = execution context, not "forever"	                                  resets between separate transactions automatically
Reset between each Batch Apex execute() call	                              a guard behaves differently in batch than in a single DML — Database.Stateful preserves instance variables, not statics
Reset for each @future / Queueable invocation	                              async work starts with a clean guard, which is usually what you want
Not reset by Test.startTest() / stopTest()	                                tests can leak state between assertions — hence @TestVisible reset()
Survives across chunks of one DML	                                          which is precisely the bug in the boolean version
Not shared across users or requests	                                        it's per-transaction memory, not a cache




Prefer idempotence over guards

The guard is a patch. The durable answer is logic that's safe to run twice:

apex
Set<Id> renamed = new Set<Id>();
for (Account a : accts) {
    if (a.Name != oldMap.get(a.Id).Name) renamed.add(a.Id);   // the change-check IS the guard
}
if (renamed.isEmpty()) return;                                 // second pass exits naturally

On the recursive pass, Trigger.old holds the values written by the first pass, so Name matches and the set is empty. No static state, no chunking bug, correct under Batch Apex. Where this works, use it and skip the guard entirely.

Decision order
Can the logic move to before? → no DML, no recursion, done.




Putting it together
AccountTrigger.trigger          2 lines, dispatch only
  └─ AccountTriggerHandler      extends TriggerHandler, routes by context, holds casts
       └─ AccountService        static methods, plain collections, bulkified
            └─ RecursionGuard   Set<Id> per logical operation

Test coverage each layer needs: service methods called directly with in-memory lists (fast, no DML); handler tested through real DML at 201+ records to prove chunking safety; guard tested by asserting the second call with the same Ids returns empty.

Natural next topic given the framework is in place: @TestSetup, Test.startTest/stopTest for limit isolation, and mocking with Test.setMock — the testing side is where the handler/service split pays for itself.
Can a field-change check make it idempotent? → use that.
Genuinely need cross-invocation state? → Set<Id> guard.
Bare static boolean → only for something that must run exactly once per transaction regardless of records, and even then document why.
